# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __int__, __float__, __complex__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __int__: false for all 10 — integer conversion is not defined.
# __float__: false for all 10 — float conversion is not defined.
# __complex__: false for all 10 — complex conversion is not defined.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. No numeric data model protocol is implemented: waves 658–672
#   established that all arithmetic (__add__/__sub__/__mul__), division
#   (__truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__), power/shift, bitwise logical, reflected
#   arithmetic, reflected bitwise, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric
#   (__neg__/__pos__/__abs__), and rounding (__invert__/__floor__/__ceil__,
#   __trunc__/__round__/__index__) operators are absent from all 10 asyncio types.
#   The numeric conversion operators tested here follow the same pattern.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   __int__, __float__, and __complex__ are absent because the event object
#   itself is not a numeric type — it is a two-state synchronization guard.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   and not exposed through any numeric data model method, including __int__,
#   __float__, or __complex__.
# asyncio.Queue note: qsize() is a method returning an int, but the queue
#   object itself defines no __int__, __float__, or __complex__. Items are
#   managed through put()/get() coroutine calls; numeric conversion of the
#   queue container is not defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

